  "prompt": "What is the average age of PhD graduates by discipline?",
  "response": "The average age of PhD graduates can vary significantly by discipline, but here are some general trends based on available data:\n\n1. **Humanities**: Graduates tend to be older, often in their late 30s or early 40s. The average age can be around 33-37 years.\n\n2. **Social Sciences**: Average ages for PhD graduates in social sciences often range from mid-30s to early 40s, with averages around 32-36 years.\n\n3. **Natural Sciences**: In fields such as biology, chemistry, and physics, graduates are typically younger, with average ages ranging from 28 to 34 years.\n\n4. **Engineering and Technology**: Similar to natural sciences, many PhD graduates in engineering and technology fields often complete their degrees in their late 20s to early 30s, with averages around 30-34 years.\n\n5. **Health Sciences**: PhD graduates in fields like nursing, pharmacy, or public health can vary but often average in their mid to late 30s.\n\n6. **Business**: Those pursuing PhDs in business-related fields often have more work experience and tend to be older, usually averaging between 31-38 years.\n\nThese averages are influenced by factors such as the length of the program, the requirement for prior degrees, and the age at which individuals typically enter graduate programs. Specific averages can also differ by university or country. For the most accurate and up-to-date statistics, checking with relevant academic institutions or research organizations may be beneficial.",
